,"1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1208":"1208","1317":"1317","england":"England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1208–":"1208–Overleden","1215–1249":"1215–1249","1236–1295":"1236–1295","1238–Male":"1238–Overleden","1240–Male":"1240–Overleden","1246–Female":"1246–Overleden","1208–Male":"1208–Overleden","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1290":"1290","1238":"1238","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1208":"1208","1317":"1317","england":"England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1208–":"1208–Deceased","1215–1249":"1215–1249","1236–1295":"1236–1295","1238–Male":"1238–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1246–Female":"1246–Deceased","1208–Male":"1208–Deceased","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1290":"1290","1238":"1238","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1208":"1208","1317":"1317","england":"England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"KEMP","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, Dutch, and North German: status name for a champion, Middle English and Middle Low German <i>kempe</i>. In the Middle Ages a champion was a professional fighter on behalf of others; for example the King's Champion, at the coronation, had the duty of issuing a general challenge to battle to anyone who denied the king's right to the throne. The Middle English word corresponds to Old English <i>cempa</i> and Old Norse <i>kempa</i> ‘warrior’; both these go back to ancient Germanic <i>campo</i> ‘warrior’, which is the source of the Dutch and North German name, corresponding to High German   Kampf  .","Dutch and North German (North Rhine-Westphalia): from the personal name <i>Kempe</i>, <i>Kampe</i>; see 1 above.","Dutch and Flemish: metonymic occupational name for someone who grew or processed hemp, from Middle Dutch <i>canep</i> ‘hemp’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kampf","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (mainly <b>Kämpf</b>): from Middle High German <i>kampf</i>, German <i>Kamf</i> ‘fight, struggle’, hence an occupational name for a champion, a professional fighter (see   Kemp  ), or a nickname for someone with a pugnacious temperament. As a Jewish name it can be artificial. Compare   Kaempf  .","German: extended form of   Kamp   1."]},{"name":"Kemps","meanings":["Dutch and Flemish: genitivized form of   Kemp   2 or 4, concentrated in North Brabant and adjacent northern Belgium.","English (London): variant of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempt","meanings":["Scottish and English: perhaps from a shortened form of the extinct Scottish surname <i>Kemptie</i>, of uncertain origin, or an altered form of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna, Ilse.  Scandinavian Detlev, Gunhild.","English, Scottish, Dutch, and North German: variant of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempel","meanings":["German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempke","meanings":["North German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempker","meanings":["German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempkes","meanings":["North German and Dutch: genitivized pet form of   Kemp   2. Particularly in North Rhine-Westphalia and adjacent Gelderland."]},{"name":"Kempner","meanings":["German:","occupational name for a champion at jousting or wrestling, an agent derivative of <i>Kempe</i> ‘fight’ (see   Kemp  ).","habitational name, with agent suffix <i>-er</i>, for someone from any of various places called Kempen (notably near Krefeld) or from Kempno near Poznań, Poland."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":7,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":16,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":51,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":82,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":107,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"James KEMP was born in 1208, in Norfolk, England. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Elizabeth BULL. He died in England."},"et":{"1208–":"1208–Surnud","1215–1249":"1215–1249","1236–1295":"1236–1295","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1246–Female":"1246–Surnud","1208–Male":"1208–Surnud","1240":"1240","1295":"1295","1290":"1290","1238":"1238","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1208":"1208","1317":"1317","england":"England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1208–":"1208–Kuollut","1215–1249":"1215–1249","1236–1295":"1236–1295","1238–Male":"1238–Kuol